<div type="definition">
<p>NEED FOOD FOR ONESELF NOW.</p>
    </div>
<div type="notes">
<div type="old-chinese-criteria">
<p>1. The most common current and general word for insufficiency of food supplies is probably jī 飢 (ant. bǎo 飽 "have eaten enough"), and this word refers to any such insufficiency, temporary or lasting, serious or minor. Presumably, the word can also refer to insufficiency of food among animals.</p>
<p>2. È 餓 refers to famine as a serious condition threatening the lives of the persons involved.</p>
<p>3. Jǐn 殣 refers to serious famine often resulting in death.</p>
<p>4. Jī 饑 (NOT ANCIENTLY HOMOPHONOUS WITH 飢 in ancient Chinese), and the rarer jín 饉 as well as the very rare qiàn 歉 refer to insufficiency of food as a result of bad harvest.</p>
<p>5. Něi 餒 refers to the state of being hungry in an individual, and at a certain time.</p>
        </div>
<div type="huang-jingui">
<p>HUANG JINGUI 2006</p>
<p>FOOD 10. 飢餓。</p>
